A user class data type supports both client-side and server-side coercions by default, unless it is declared non-nullable. For example, the following statement declares an instance variable of type IntegerObject with a null value:

IntegerObject i;

However, the next statement causes client-side coercion because the string "2" cannot be converted to a valid integer without truncation:

i = "2";

To avoid client-side coercion, use the `not null` clause for any class data type that can have a value of null. For example, use this statement instead:

IntegerObject i(null);
